Preheat your oven to 200°C and bring a #large saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Peel and chop the @potatoes{700%g} into 4cm chunks. Pat the @pork roasting joint{450%g} dry with some #kitchen roll{}, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and drizzle with @oil{}. Heat a #frying pan{} over high heat and brown the pork all over, ~{2%minutes}, turning often. Transfer to a #baking tray{} and lay the @British streaky bacon{4%slices} rashers over the pork, tucking them under at the bottom.

Roast the pork on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{40-55%mins} (depending on size).

> The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Pour a good glug of @oil{} onto another baking tray and pop in your oven. Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges have softened when you poke them with a knife.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{}, pop back into the pan then sprinkle on @plain flour{12%g}. Give your pan a shake to fluff up the potatoes. Take your hot baking tray out of your oven, carefully transfer your potatoes onto it in a single layer, turning in the oil. Season with @salt{}. Roast the potatoes on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{45-50%minutes}, turn halfway through. Wash your #saucepan{} and set aside - you'll use it later.

Meanwhile, cut the @red cabbage{1} in half through the root, remove the triangle root in the middle and discard, then slice thinly. Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large saucepan on medium high heat. Once the oil is hot, add the cabbage, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, and stir fry for ~{2%minutes}. Pour in the @soy sauce{25%ml}, @balsamic vinegar{12%ml}, @sugar{1} and @water{350%ml}. Stir and bring to a simmer, then reduce the heat to medium low, cover with a #lid{} and leave to cook until the cabbage is tender, ~{10-12%minutes}. Stir twice in this time. Once tender, remove the lid, increase the heat to medium and cook until the liquid has reduced, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pop a saucepan on medium high heat and add @unsalted butter{15%g}. Allow the butter to melt, then stir in the remaining @plain flour{12%g}. You've made a roux! Cook until the roux is a medium brown colour and gradually stir in the @water{400%ml}, @chicken stock paste{1%tsp} and @onion marmalade{40%g}. Bring to the boil, stirring out any lumps that form. Lower the heat and simmer until the gravy has thickened to your liking, ~{10-15%minutes}. When the pork is ready, allow to rest, wrapped in #foil{} for ~{10-15%minutes} before slicing.

Fill your pan with water and @salt{1/2%tsp} and pop on high heat.

Get any washing up done. Once your water is boiling, and once everything is nearly ready, add the @green beans{150%g} to the water and simmer until tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Once cooked drain in a colander. Stir the remaining @unsalted butter{15%g} into the red cabbage, taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if you feel it needs it. Add any pork resting juices to the gravy if it needs thinning slightly, reheat if necessary. Slice the pork thinly and add to the plate along with the veggies. Pour over the gravy and enjoy!